## Executive Summary

The US Government is the leading humanitarian donor, contributing nearly
\$296 million in 2025 with an overall funding trajectory marked by
significant yearly fluctuations but sustained high volume. It allocates
about 32% of funding as earmarked, surpassing other donors, reflecting a
strategic focus on priority regions and sectors. The USA’s geographic
reach expanded dramatically from 7 to nearly 98 countries between
2022-2025, signaling broad global engagement and diverse funding needs.
With frequent large transactions averaging \$3.1 million, the US
supports medium to large-scale interventions. Fundraisers should
emphasize US leadership, align proposals with shifting regional
priorities, and time submissions to leverage funding peaks and
earmarking trends.

## Diversification

countries, which could mean broader impact but also necessitates

## Volatility

This analysis reviews funding transactions from the United States
government, with data captured over a period spanning February 2023 to
September 2025. The dataset includes 1460 individual transaction
records, each detailing the transaction date and value in USD. The
average transaction amount was 3.1 million dollars, significantly higher
than the benchmark average of 2.5 million dollars from the top 10 other
donors. Additionally, the average number of transactions per year stood
at roughly 487, more than double the benchmark average of 232
transactions annually. These figures highlight that US government
funding is characterized by both larger individual contributions and
more frequent disbursements compared to its peer donors. The data
visualization includes points for individual transactions, trend lines,
and smoothed ribbons that indicate trends and volatility over time. This
suggests a funding pattern that, while substantial in volume, may also
fluctuate, which humanitarian planning should consider for
sustainability and program continuity. For proposal writers, this
implies that US government funding can support medium to large-scale
interventions with relatively stable transaction frequency but requires
attention to potential variability in amounts. Continuous engagement and
monitoring of funding flows are advisable to mitigate risks related to
volatility and to optimize resource allocation.
